yield: for stockinpiggle pork spare ribs (200g ish)
uses:
  - crackling
ingredients:
  - item: pork spare ribs
    mass: 200
    basis: true
    note: ~3×3×15cm strips, skin removed
components:
  - name: braise
    ingredients:
      - item: white miso
        mass: 40
        qty: 2
        unit: tbsp
        note: red for more funk
      - item: maple syrup
        mass: 40
        qty: 2
        unit: tbsp
        note: dark/grade B preferred
      - item: soy or tamari
        mass: 8
        qty: 1
        unit: tbsp
      - item: ginger
        qty: 1
        unit: tsp
        note: grated
      - item: garlic clove
        qty: 2
        unit: ea
        note: grated
      - item: rice vinegar or mirin
        mass: 5
        qty: 1
        unit: tsp
        note: try 50:50
      - item: water or stock
        qty: 3
        unit: tbsp
        note: 3-4 tbsp, to dilute
  - name: cook
    steps:
      - marinate a few hours (max ~12hr — miso enzymes turn meat mealy past that)
      - foil parcel with just a few tbsp of marinade per strip — braise, not swim
      - 140-150°C conventional for 90min–1h45 (check at 75 mins) until yielding and wobbly; no springiness when pressed
      - open foil; lift pork onto rack; pour braising liquid into saucepan
      - reduce braising liquid to thick, glossy, mahogany glaze
      - 'split glaze: ~2/3 cooking, ~1/3 reserve for serving'
      - brush cooking glaze onto pork; blast 200-220°C fan-forced (on rack not back in foil) for 5-10 mins watching closely - second coat halfway through for thicker lacquer; blowtorch works great here
      - rest, then slice perpendicular into 1.5-2cm pieces
  - name: serving glaze
    steps:
      - 'loosen reserved glaze: squeeze of lime or few drops rice vinegar'
      - half-tsp fresh grated ginger stirred in off heat
      - thin with a splash of water if needed
      - tiny dab of fresh miso if the flavour has gone flat in the reduction
      - spoon over sliced pork at the plate
  - name: plating
    steps:
      - slices slightly overlapping, cut-side up to show the fat/meat layers
      - serving glaze drizzled over
      - thinly sliced spring onion or toasted sesame seeds to finish
notes: |
  [ why so little liquid in the parcel ]
  The braising liquid that comes out should be a few tablespoons of intense, slightly fatty,
  mahogany-coloured liquid — not a cup of pale water. A lot of liquid dilutes the pork's own
  rendered fat and gelatin into the surrounding water rather than concentrating it in the glaze.
  The small amount also keeps equilibrium in the parcel: instead of leaching flavour out of
  the meat (the direction of stock-making), the seasoning concentrates around it.

  The foil traps steam that circulates at ~100°C, cooking evenly from all sides. Bottom of the
  meat braises and absorbs flavour; top half cooks in steam. Rendered fat stays in the pool
  rather than floating on a cup of water that has to be skimmed.

  [ the two-glaze principle ]
  Glaze brushed on before the high-heat blast caramelises and deepens — great for colour and
  lacquer, but the bright top notes (ginger zing, vinegar tang, fresh miso funk) cook out.
  Reserved glaze keeps those intact. Layering them gives a caramelised surface hit first, then
  brighter aromatic flavour as you chew. Always hold some back.

  [ miso & maple notes ]
  White miso: sweeter, milder — good starting point. Red miso: funkier, more assertive.
  Dark/grade B maple brings woody depth; light maple reads as just sweet. Miso is already salty
  — taste before adding more soy or salt. Proteases in miso tenderise aggressively, so don't
  push the marinade past ~12hr.

  [ on the skin ]
  If not dried overnight, remove skin and do crackling separately (see crackling recipe).
  A wet, glazed skin under a high-heat ramp will go leathery rather than crackled.
